-- 
Ringgit Drops as Credit Suisse Cuts GDP Forecast; Bonds Advance

-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 
2011-08-02T08:43:40Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-02/ringgit-weakens-as-u-s-manufacturing-slowdown-may-hurt-exports.html
Malaysia ’s ringgit weakened,
retreating from near a 14-year high, as signs the U.S. economic
recovery is losing momentum dimmed the outlook for exports.  The currency had its biggest gain of 2011 yesterday as U.S.
lawmakers forged an agreement to raise the federal debt limit to
avoid a default, spurring demand for riskier assets. The
prospect of exports moderating prompted Credit Suisse Group AG
to lower its 2011 economic growth forecast for Malaysia to 5.3
percent from 5.6 percent, according to an Aug. 1 research note.
 Government bonds  advanced.  “There’s a bit of concern about the downside risk to
growth with the latest economic reports,” said Saktiandi Supaat,
head of foreign-exchange research at Malayan Banking Bhd. in
Singapore. “This could delay further policy tightening” in the
region, he said.  The ringgit dropped 0.6 percent to 2.9573 per dollar as of
4:40 p.m. in  Kuala Lumpur , having jumped 0.9 percent yesterday,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg. The currency touched
2.9335 on July 27, the strongest level since September 1997.  Data due Aug. 4 are expected to show overseas sales rose
5.8 percent in June following a 5.4 percent advance the previous
month, according to the median estimate in a Bloomberg survey.  The U.S. Institute for Supply Management’s factory index
slumped to a two-year low of 50.9 in July from 55.3 a month
earlier, the group said. Figures lower than 50 signal
contraction. A Markit/HSBC Holdings Plc report yesterday showed
China’s PMI manufacturing index contracted in July for the first
time in a year.  Bonds Advance  Malaysia shipped a combined 21 percent of its goods to
 China  and the U.S. in the first five months of this year,
according to trade ministry statistics.  Three-year notes gained for a third day, pushing yields to
the lowest in more than seven weeks.  The yield on the 3.434 percent notes due August 2014
dropped three basis points, or 0.03 percentage point, to 3.19
percent, the least since June 10, according to Bursa Malaysia.
The price rose 0.1, or 1 ringgit per 1,000 ringgit face amount,
to 100.70.  Bank Negara Malaysia  kept its overnight policy rate at 3
percent on July 7, after lifting it once in 2011 and three times
in 2010. Policy makers next meet on Sept. 8.  To contact the reporter on this story:
David Yong in  Singapore  at 
 dyong@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
